			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: haste and slow stacking?<a name="66897"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 14 04 1:46 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I guess that is a no.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
If you're looking for a quick one-sentence answer without doing any research, then yeah - the answer is no.
<br />

<br />
If you take the time to look at the references you were offered and research the songs, you would see that it isn't that cut and dried.
<br />

<br />
The slow components of different songs and spells do not combine effects.  In other words, a shaman's 75% slow and my 55% slow do not combine to create a 130% slow.  However, both spells CAN be in effect on a mob meaning if one gets dispelled the other is still there.  If I land Requeim of Time during the pull and a Shaman then lands Turgur's, Requeim doesn't vanish -- it stays in place for the full one-minute duration.  Many of our slow songs have additional components to them, too -- the level 20 AE Largo's, for instance, has an AC debuff.  It will not be knocked off by an enchanter or shaman slow, so it is conceivably useful to keep using your slows even with an enchanter or shaman around.
<br />

<br />
Haste is even more complex.  Here's the short version.  There is spell haste, item haste, stacking haste, and stacking over-haste.  Enchanters, shaman, bards and any right-click or proc type of haste is generally spell haste.  Item haste is permanent haste you get from just wearing the item.  You can only gain the benefits of one of each of these - in othe words, if a bard is singing celerity, a shaman casting alacrity, and an enchanter casting speed of the shissar, and an epic bard procs Dance of the Blade, you will have 60% haste -- the haste from Shissar.  You may still have other benefits, like the strength or attack buff from Dance, but only 60% haste.  You can wear 10 different items with permanent haste but only the highest one counts.  What's more, each class has a specific haste cap for whatever your level happens to be.  For a 65 bard, for instance, that cap is 100%.  The combination of your spell haste, item haste and any stacking bard haste songs cannot exceed 100%.  If a bard adds stacking over-haste songs, these can add onto the total up to a maximum (so far) of 30%.
<br />

<br />
For details, click on the guides section and look it up.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
